cif"],regex:/\.bcif(?:\.gz)?$/i,type:"structure",name:"BinaryCIF"},cif:{value:"cif",extensions:["cif","mmcif"],regex:/\.cif(?:\.gz)?$/i,type:"structure",name:"mmCIF"},pdb:{value:"pdb",extensions:["pdb","ent"],regex:/\.(?:pdb|ent)(?:\.gz)?$/i,type:"structure",name:"PDB"},ccp4:{value:"ccp4",extensions:["ccp4"],regex:/\.ccp4$/i,type:"volume",name:"CCP4"}},Cl={goFooter:"<i><strong>Note:</strong> Not all Entry IDs/chains have been mapped to GO terms.</i>",goHeader:'<p style="font-size:12px;"><i><strong>Note:</strong> to search by GO ID it is only necessary to enter the numeric portion of the ID, for example, to search for <strong>"GO:0007610"</strong>, enter <strong>"761"</strong>.</i></p>',headers:{atc:'<p>The <a href="http://www.whocc.no/atc/structure_and_principles/" target="_blank">Anatomical Therapeutic Chemical (ATC)</a> Classification System is used for the classification of drugs. It is controlled by the <a href="http://www.whocc.no/" target="_blank">WHO Collaborating Centre for Drug Statistics Methodology</a>.</p><p>Here you can <b>browse</b> or search for an ATC name or ATC code of small molecule drugs and view the number of associated Molecular Definitions present in the Chemical component or BIRD dictionaries.</p>',biological_process:'<p>Vocabulary terms describing biological processes developed by the <a href="http://www.geneontology.org/" target="_blank">Gene Ontology Consortium (GO)</a> have been mapped to PDB entities by <a href="http://www.ebi.ac.uk/pdbe/docs/sifts/" target="_blank">SIFTS</a>.</p><p>Here you can <b>browse</b> this Biological Process tree by selecting a GO term, or enter a GO term in the search box to identify the corresponding PDB entities.</p>',card:'<p>The <a href="https://card.mcmaster.ca/home" target="_blank">Comprehensive Antibiotic Resistance Database (CARD)</a> is a curated bioinformatics database that uses Antimicrobial Resistance Gene (ARG) detection models to identify resistance genes, their products, and associated antibiotics resistance phenotypes and presents them organized by the Antibiotic Resistance Ontology (ARO).</p><p>Exact and close matches to the resistance genes were identified in PDB entries and annotated with relevant ARO identifiers and additional information antibiotics resistance related information. For example, you can search for all PDB sequences annotated as &quot;determinant of antibiotic resistance&quot; by clicking on (<a href="/search?request=%7B%22query%22%3A%7B%22type%22%3A%22group%22%2C%22nodes%22%3A%5B%7B%22type%22%3A%22group%22%2C%22nodes%22%3A%5B%7B%22type%22%3A%22group%22%2C%22nodes%22%3A%5B%7B%22type%22%3A%22group%22%2C%22nodes%22%3A%5B%7B%22type%22%3A%22terminal%22%2C%22service%22%3A%22text%22%2C%22parameters%22%3A%7B%22attribute%22%3A%22rcsb_polymer_entity_annotation.annotation_lineage.id%22%2C%22operator%22%3A%22exact_match%22%2C%22value%22%3A%22ARO%3A3000000%22%7D%7D%2C%7B%22type%22%3A%22terminal%22%2C%22service%22%3A%22text%22%2C%22parameters%22%3A%7B%22attribute%22%3A%22rcsb_polymer_entity_annotation.type%22%2C%22operator%22%3A%22exact_match%22%2C%22value%22%3A%22CARD%22%7D%7D%5D%2C%22logical_operator%22%3A%22and%22%2C%22label%22%3A%22nested-attribute%22%7D%5D%2C%22logical_operator%22%3A%22and%22%7D%5D%2C%22logical_operator%22%3A%22and%22%2C%22label%22%3A%22text%22%7D%5D%2C%22logical_operator%22%3A%22and%22%7D%2C%22return_type%22%3A%22polymer_entity%22%2C%22request_options%22%3A%7B%7D%7D">ARO:3000000</a>).</p><p>Here you can <b>browse</b> protein entities in the PDB by the ARO &quot;determinant of antibiotic resistance&quot; types, &quot;gene families&quot;, and &quot;genes&quot; to identify associated structures.</p>',cath:'<p>The <a href="http://www.cathdb.info/" target="_blank">CATH</a> browser is a hierarchical classification of protein domain structures, which clusters proteins at four major levels, Class(C), Architecture(A), Topology(T) and Homologous superfamily (H). Class, derived from secondary structure content, is assigned for more than 90% of protein structures automatically. Architecture, which describes the gross orientation of secondary structures, independent of connectivities, is currently assigned manually. The topology level clusters structures according to their toplogical   connections and numbers of secondary structures. The homologous superfamilies cluster proteins with highly similar structures and functions. The assignments of structures to toplogy families and homologous superfamilies are made by sequence and structure comparisons.</p><p>Here you can <b>browse</b> or search for PDB structures by CATH IDs or domain/fold names.</p>',cellular_component:'<p>This cellular component browser organizes protein entities by vocabulary terms describing cellular component locations developed by the <a href="http://www.geneontology.org/" target="_blank">Gene Ontology Consortium (GO)</a> have been mapped to PDB entities by <a href="http://www.ebi.ac.uk/pdbe/docs/sifts/" target="_blank">SIFTS</a>.</p><p>Here you can <b>browse</b> the cellular component tree by selecting a GO term, or enter a GO term in the search box to identify the corresponding PDB entities.</p>',diseases:'<p>The Disease Ontology browser organizes protein sequences by <a href="https://mondo.monarchinitiative.org/" target="_blank">Mondo Disease Ontology</a> terms describing disease definitions developed by the Monarch Initiative team. The definitions have been mapped to UniProt sequences by the Knowledge Management Center (KMC) for the Illuminating the Druggable Genome (IDG) program and available for PDB entities mapped to UniProt.</p>',ec:'<p>The EC (Enzyme Commission) browser presents proteins in the PDB based on the type of enzyme function it performs. Enzymes are classified based on the recommendations of the Nomenclature Committee of the International Union of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology (<a href="https://www.qmul.ac.uk/sbcs/iubmb/enzyme/" target="_blank">IUBMB</a>). For each enzyme in the archive an EC number has been provided (see <a href="http://www.enzyme-database.org/" target="_blank">EC</a>). These assignments are based on UniProtKB/GenBank/KEGG/author specified mapping of the enzyme to EC numbers. </p><p>Here you can <strong>browse</strong> the EC tree by an enzyme or enzyme class name, <strong>view</strong> the number of associated PDB proteins, and <strong>search</strong> for the specific associated structures either by enzyme name or by partial/full EC number.</p>',ecod:'<p>The <a href="http://prodata.swmed.edu/ecod/" target="_blank">Evolutionary Classification Of protein Domains (ECOD)</a> browser classifies protein structures according to evolutionary     relationships: (A) architecture, (X) possible homology, (H) homology, (T) topology, (F): Family. ECOD is updated regularly after new PDB releases are classified.</p><p>Here you can <b>browse</b> through PDB structures by their ECOD classification.</p>',genome_location:'<p>The genome browser is a hierarchical representation of structures from genomes of various organisms. RCSB PDB has mapped the structures to the chromosomal loci based on <a href="https://www.uniprot.org/" target="_blank">UniProtKB</a>/<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/genbank/" target="_blank">GenBank</a> accession numbers associated with the structures and the loci. The genomes represented are a subset of the genomes in the NCBI genome database and whose curated sequences for genetic loci are archived at <a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/query.fcgi?db=gene" target="_blank">Entrez Gene</a>. The top level in the hierarchy is the organism\'s genome. Each genome expands into chromosomes which in turn expand into a list of loci on the chromosomes. Each locus is a link to retrieve structures associated with that locus.</p><p>Here you can <strong>browse</strong> by Gene name, <strong>view</strong> the number of associated PDB structures, and <strong>search</strong> for the specific associated structures. Genes may be <strong>searched</strong> using their <strong>names</strong>.</p>',membrane:'<p>The mpstruc browser organizes membrane proteins with known 3D structure. Transmembrane protein annotations in the <a href="http://blanco.biomol.uci.edu/mpstruc/" target="_blank">mpstruc database</a> (Stephen White, UC Irvine) and UniProt is manually curated based upon literature surveys.</p><p>Here you can <b>browse</b> through membrane associated proteins by their membrane association, protein names, their functions etc.</p>',mesh:'<p>The MeSH browser organizes PDB structures by a hierarchical set of keywords applied to publication that describe PDB structures. The majority of PDB structures have associated a primary citation that is listed on the Structure Summary page. That citation includes an abstract and keywords. The <a href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/mesh/" target="_blank">MeSH (Medical Subject Headings)</a> are the keywords or MeSH terms indexed by the National Library of Medicine (NLM) by a human annotator.</p><p>Here you can <b>browse</b> the MeSH tree to find all structures at a given level of the tree that have an abstract which include the selected MeSH term as a keyword.</p>',molecular_function:'<p>The molecular Function browser organizes protein structures in the PDB by vocabulary terms describing molecular function developed by the <a href="http://www.geneontology.org/" target="_blank">Gene Ontology Consortium (GO)</a> have been mapped to PDB entities by <a href="http://www.ebi.ac.uk/pdbe/docs/sifts/" target="_blank">SIFTS</a>.</p><p>Here you can <b>browse</b> the Molecular Function tree by selecting a GO term, or enter a GO term in the search box to identify the corresponding PDB entities.</p>',opm:'<p>The OPM browser organizes membrane associated proteins by their spatial arrangements with respect to membrane\'s lipid bilayer. The classification is based on the&nbsp; <a href="https://opm.phar.umich.edu/" target="_blank">Orientations of Proteins in Membranes (OPM) database</a> (Andrei Lomize, University of Michigan) and UniProt.</p><p>Here you can <b>browse</b> through protein entities in the PDB based on their membrane association.</p>',scop:'<p>The SCOP/SCOP-e browser organizes proteins into groups that have structural similarities that may share evolutionary origins.</p><p> The SCOP database, was created by manual inspection. Abetted by a battery of automated methods, this database aims to provide a detailed and comprehensive description of structural and evolutionary relationships between all proteins whose structure is known. The legacy SCOP classifications (version 1.75) was last released in 2009.</p><p>The <a href="https://scop.berkeley.edu/" target="_blank">SCOP-e</a> project uses a combination of manual curation and rigorously validated automated methods to classify PDB structures, especially the newer structures. It provides access to data found in all releases of the SCOP and Astral databases that feature stable identifiers.</p><p>Here you can <b>browse</b> through PDB structures by their SCOP/SCOP-e classification.</p>',scop2:'<p><a href="https://www.ebi.ac.uk/pdbe/scop" target="_blank"><b>SCOP:</b></a> Structural Classification of Proteins. Nearly all proteins have structural similarities with other proteins and, in some of these cases, share a common evolutionary origin. The SCOP database, created by manual inspection and abetted by a battery of automated methods, aims to provide a detailed and comprehensive description of the structural and evolutionary relationships between all proteins whose structure is known. As such, it provides a broad survey of all known protein folds, detailed information about the close relatives of any particular protein, and a framework for future research and classification.</p>',symmetry:"<p>The Protein symmetry browser organizes protein structures in the PDB by the presence of global, local, and pseudo point group symmetries. Protein symmetry is calculated for all      protein complexes by the PDB, and updated weekly.</p><p>Here you can <b>browse</b> assemblies in the PDB by various global, local, and pseudo symmetries.</p>",taxonomy:'<p>The Source Organism browser is a hierarchical representation of all organisms in the <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/taxonomy" target="_blank">NCBI Taxonomy database</a>. Only organisms that are the source of naturally-occurring polymers (proteins and nucleic acids) whose structures are in the PDB are listed as active links in the browser. The PDB source organism assignment is based on author/<a href="https://www.uniprot.org/" target="_blank">UniProtKB</a> specified mapping of polypeptides.</p><p>Here you can <b>browse</b> protein entities by source organism, and then search for the specific associated structures.</p>'},footers:{ecod:"<h5>References</h5><ul><li>H. Cheng, R. D. Schaeffer, Y. Liao, L. N. Kinch, J. Pei, S. Shi, B. H. Kim, N. V. Grishin. (2014) ECOD: An evolutionary classification of protein domains. PLoS Comput Biol 10(12): e1003926.</li><li>H. Cheng, Y. Liao, R. D. Schaeffer, N. V. Grishin. (2015) Manual classification strategies in the ECOD database. Proteins 83(7): 1238-1251.</li></ul>"},helpLinks:{atc:"atc",biological_process:"biological-process",cath:"cath",cellular_component:"cellular-component",diseases:"disease-ontology",ec:"enzyme-classification",ecod:"ecod",genome_location:"genome-location",membrane:"membrane-protein-mpstruc",mesh:"mesh",molecular_function:"molecular-function",opm:"membrane-protein-opm",scop:"scop-e",scop2:"scop2",symmetry:"protein-symmetry",taxonomy:"source-organism",card:"card"}},Ol=["MemProtMD","OPM","mpstruc","PDBTM"],Tl={},Nl={},Al=[],Rl={},Il={},$l=[],ql={},Pl={custom_report:"Custom",entry_id:"Entry ID",upload:"File Upload",url:"File URL",evalue_cutoff:"E-Value Cutoff",identity_cutoff:"Identity Cutoff",sequence_type:"Sequence Type",pattern_type:"Mode",similarity_type:"Similarity Type",ptmscore_cutoff:"Predicted Score Cutoff",target_search_space:"Search Targtes",label_asym_id:"Chain ID",stru